chapter.section:
Numbers are not the only information for a plot: generally it is necessary to know who is plotted respect who, and some other facultative things like &track; names, units, etc... These informations are passed with a data header; the syntax adopted by ∓ privileges briefness over standardization (like &XML; format).
With the header directive the following information can be specified:
Expected data columns number Strings specifying column names, units of measure and data type Columns relationship (dependent and independent variables, real and imaginary part of a complex &track; -not yet ready-) Linear transformations (scale and offset) on columns
The header argument consists of a string composed by a sequence of data columns delcaration; each declaration is composed by a string enclosed by <> organized as follows:
<column_name(plotted_respect)[unit of measure and scaling]> The first string assigns an unique identifier (among the whole file) to the associated data column. Rounded brackets enclose informations about the independent variable; it could be another column name or a rescaled index (self declared independent variable). Squared brackets enclose information about units, scaling and data type.
If you desire a column name including brackets, use the escape character \ as in this example.
#header <z> <y\(x\)(z)>
This declares a first column named z and a second column named y(x) plotted respect column z.
I think the best way to introduce header syntax is by examples:
/* In this header example will be specified that the following data are composed by three columns; the first column is a motor torque that must be plotted respect the second column, a speed, and the third is a current that must be plotted simply respect its samples index, so: .declare three data columns, giving names .plot the first respect the second .plot the third simply by its index */ #header <T(w)><w><i()> 0 0 0 6.32 2 1.24 ...
/* In the following example some information were added: .Torque is measured in tenth of Nm .Speed is measured in rpm .Current is measured in tens of A every 0.5ms */ #header <T(w)[0.1Nm]><w[rpm]><i([0.5ms])[10A]> 0 0 0 6.32 2 1.24 ...
/* In the following example some information were added: .Fix a current offset of -0.7A .The current independent variable is now labeled 't' .Current's measure time 't' starts at 100ms */ #header <T(w)[0.1Nm]><w[rpm]><i(t[0.5ms+100])[10A-0.7]> 0 0 0 6.32 2 1.24 ...
/* There is actually another information you can embed in the data column declaration, its data type: */ #header <time [4E-3s]><AnOut[0.1V+0.01|u16|]> 1 -32768 2 -32768 ... /* The u16 tells that the column is composed by 16bit unsigned integers, so -1 will be casted to 65535, -32768 to 32768 and so on */
The number of declared column must exactly match the actual number of data columns; the only exception is when there is only one column of data, which will be splitted according to header declaration (see Split directive).
Here some specifications:
Column declarations are enclosed by <>; characters outside are ignored (not ready) Declaration string can be prefixed and enclosed by {}. Re prefix indicates that column is a real part of a complex number, while Im indicates the imaginary part (prefixes are case sensitive) A single column declaration is composed by three consecutive parts (spaces are ignored):
Column name (mandatory): an unambiguous label starting with an alphabetic character Abscissa data (optional): a string enclosed by () indicating that column is an ordinate; the string can be empty, an existing column label, or an index scale composed by a rescaling factor, unit label and offset Unit data (optional): a string composed by rescaling factor, unit label and an offset enclosed by [] (spaces are ignored). Here you can append also a data type declaration such as |u16|; u stands for unsigned integer, i for signed integer; this prefix is followed by a bit number. The effect is that each data is casted to type and then a bit mask is applied.
Names and units are case sensitive If all columns corresponds to abscissa, they will be converted as indexed ordinates
The default characters that identify a column field in header are same characters of &XML; tags: <>. As explicit developer choice, user cannot modify this default. Note that initially were adopted the 'guillemet' or french quotation marks « (Alt+0171) » (Alt+0187), but finally this choice was discarded to avoid &ASCII; extension chars.
// Note that extra-spaces are simply ignored // by the parser.
// plot 'y1' vs 'x' and 'y2' vs 'z' #header <x> <y1(x)> <z> <y2(z)>
// plot all vs their ordinal index // 'c' is rescaled and measured in 'mm' #header < t()> < a() > <b()> <c() [0.1mm]> // or in a more concise form: #header < t> < a > <b> <c [0.1mm]> // Note that the following plots only 'a' vs // its idx, because the remaining columns are // taken as unused abscissas: #header < t> < a() > <b> <c [0.1mm]>
// plot 'a','c' vs 't'; 'b1' vs its index #header <t [ms]> <a(t) [cm]> <b1() > <c(t)[Km]>
// plot 'I','v' vs 'r' // 'I' is measured in A, rescaled respect 10A, // with an offset correction of -0.43A #header < I(r)[10A-0.43]> <r [ohm]> <v(r) [V]>
// Different abscissas: a power (acquired in // watt) vs current and a voltage vs a // different current 'i2' #header <i1 [A]> <i2 [A]> < P(i1) [.001KW]> <v(i2) [V]>
// Index rescaling // plot 'x' vs its idx measured in newton, // 'y' vs 'csi' // 'z' vs its idx multiplied by '0.2 m' #header <x([1N])> <y(csi)> <csi [m]> <z([.2m])>
// A synchronized time acquisition of three quantities: // 'x' with a sample frequency of 2KHz, // 'y' with a sample frequency of 1KHz, // 'z' with a sample frequency of 0.5KHz #header <x([.5ms])> <y([1ms])> <z([2ms])>
// A feature yet to come: polar plot of complex datas // A space vector current (Id,Iq) measured at time 't' #header <t[ms]><Re{I(t)[A]}><Im{I(t)[A]}>
